    <section id="fs-id1587093" class="further-research" type="further-research">
    <title>Further Research</title>
    <para xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0" id="import-auto-id1169033100416">The Beats were a counterculture that birthed an entire movement of art, music, and literature—much of which is still highly regarded and studied today. The man responsible for naming the generation was Jack Kerouac; however, the man responsible for introducing the world to that generation was John Clellon Holmes, a writer often lumped in with the group. In 1952 he penned an article for the <emphasis effect="italics">New York Times Magazine</emphasis> titled, “This Is the Beat Generation.” Read that article and learn more about Clellon Holmes and the Beats: <link url="http://openstaxcollege.org/l/The-Beats">http://openstaxcollege.org/l/The-Beats</link></para><para xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0" id="import-auto-id1169033069480">Popular culture meets counterculture in this as Oprah Winfrey interacts with members of the Yearning for Zion cult. Read about it here: <link url="http://openstaxcollege.org/l/Oprah">http://openstaxcollege.org/l/Oprah</link></para></section>



